library(MASS)
df <- read.table("../data/1.txt")
columns.for.fitting <- c("body.fat", 'age', 'weight', 'height', 'BMI', 'neck', 'chest', 'abdomen', 'hip', 'thigh', 'knee', 'ankle', 'bicep', 'forearm', 'wrist')
df <- df[, columns.for.fitting]
names(df)[names(df)=="body.fat"] <- "Y"
model <- lm(Y ~ ., data=df)
summary(model)

Determination coefficient for the reduced model is 0.7383. But let’s plot all the data and try to stare at it really hard.

library(knitr)
library(lattice)
library(e1071)
library(corrplot)
library(latticeExtra)
## Loading required package: RColorBrewer
df <- df[-c(39), ]
plotVariable <- function(param) {
  formula <- reformulate(termlabels = param, response = 'Y')
  xyplot(formula, panel=function(...) {  
  panel.xyplot(...)
  panel.loess(...)
  }, data = df, xlab = param, ylab = "Y")
}

plotVariables <- function() {
  for (i in colnames(df)[-1]) {
    print(plotVariable(i)) 
  }
}
plotVariables()

We cannot help but notice an outlier to the right on plots ankle (although ankle has many outliers), abdomen, weight, BMI, neck, chest, hip, thigh, knee, whose measurements are high while body fat is relatively low, number 39. Let’s remove him and fit again.
